Warm Up: Brief Financial Data

  1. Natively in R, you have access to sample data sets of prominent stocks over time. Well be using EuStockMarkets for this question. Type help(EuStockMarkets) to learn more. From these data, pull specifically the DAX index. For all questions in this assignment, youre welcome to normalize (or dont!) how you see fit, but, if you choose to, please document what youre doing and why for the grader. Its not necessary for the purpose of this assignment.
EUDAXdata <- EuStockMarkets[,"DAX"] # extract only DAX time series
  1. These are annual European Stock Data from 1990 onward. Create a rudimentary plot of the data. Make the line blue. Give an informative title. Label the axes accurately. In 1997, an event happened you want to indicate; add a vertical red line to your plot which divides pre-1997 and post-1997 information.
plot(EUDAXdata, col="blue", xlab="Time (Years)", ylab="Closing Price", main="Closing Price for Germany DAX (Ibis) Stock Index") # plot data
# draw red vertical line for 1997
abline(v = 1997, col="red")

  1. Decompose the time series into its components (i.e., trend, seasonality, random). Keep in mind that this is a multiplicative model you want. Create a plot of all decomposed components. As before, make all lines blue and have a vertical divider at the year 1997.
EUDAXdataDecomp <- decompose(EUDAXdata, type="multiplicative")
plot(EUDAXdataDecomp, col="blue")
# draw red vertical line for 1997
abline(v = 1997, col="red")

Temperature Data

  1. Using the maxtemp dataset granted by loading fpp2, there are maximum annual temperature data in Celsius. For more information, use help(maxtemp). To see what youre looking at, execute the command in Examples in the help document.

  2. We are only concerned with information after 1990. Please eliminate unwanted information or subset information we care about.

tempdata <- window(maxtemp,start=1990,end=2016) # subset maxtemp for years 1990-2016
head(tempdata) # examine top and bottom of data
## Time Series:
## Start = 1990 
## End = 1995 
## Frequency = 1 
## 1990 1991 1992 1993 1994 1995 
## 39.0 41.3 38.7 37.8 38.9 39.7
tail(tempdata)
## Time Series:
## Start = 2011 
## End = 2016 
## Frequency = 1 
## 2011 2012 2013 2014 2015 2016 
## 39.5 39.7 41.5 43.7 42.7 42.9
  1. Utilize SES to predict the next five years of maximum temperatures in Melbourne. Plot this information, including the prior information and the forecast. Add the predicted value line across 1990-present as a separate line, preferably blue. So, to review, you should have your fit, the predicted value line overlaying it, and a forecast through 2021, all on one axis. Find the AICc of this fitted model. You will use that information later.
# create SES fitted data set, and predict 5 (years) into future
tempses <- ses(tempdata, alpha=0.8, h=5) 

# plot the timeseries data overlaying predicted fit and adding forecast
plot(tempses,PI=FALSE,xlab="Year",ylab="Max Temp in C",main="Maximum Temperature in Celcius by Year (with Forecast)",fcol="white",type="o")

# add fitted predicted values
lines(fitted(tempses), col="blue", type="o")

# add forecast
lines(tempses$mean, col="blue", type="o")

# display AICc for future comparison
tempses$model$aicc
## [1] 148.3759
  1. Now use a damped Holts linear trend to also predict out five years. Make sure initial=optimal. As above, create a similar plot to 1C, but use the Holt fit instead.
# create damped Holt's linear trend
tempholt <- holt(tempdata, alpha=0.8, beta=0.2, damped=TRUE, initial="optimal", h=5)

# plot the timeseries data overlaying predicted fit and adding forecast
plot(tempholt,PI=FALSE,xlab="Year",ylab="Max Temp in C",main="Maximum Temperature in Celcius by Year (with Forecast)",fcol="white",type="o")

# add fitted predicted values
lines(fitted(tempholt), col="blue", type="o")

# add forecast
lines(tempholt$mean, col="blue", type="o")

  1. Compare the AICc of the ses() and holt() models. Which model is better here?
# display AICc for comparison
tempholt$model$aicc
## [1] 157.9802

Using the ses() and holt() parameters as shown in the R code above the SES model shows a smaller AICc (148.38) versus Holt (157.98).

The Wands Choose the Wizard

  1. Utilize the dygraphs library. Read in both Unit11TimeSeries_Ollivander and _Gregorovitch.csv as two different data frames. They do not have headers, so make sure you account for that. This is a time series of Wands sold over years.
# load data
Ollivander <- read.csv("Unit11TimeSeries_Ollivander.csv", header=FALSE)
Gregorovitch <- read.csv("Unit11TimeSeries_Gregorovitch.csv", header=FALSE)

# apply column names
colnames(Ollivander) <- c("DateYears", "Wands")
colnames(Gregorovitch) <- c("DateYears", "Wands")

  1. You dont have your information in the proper format! In both data sets, youll need to first convert the date-like variable to an actual Date class.
  2. Use the library xts (and the xts() function in it) to make each data frame an xts object (effectively, a time series). Youll want to order.by the Date variable.
# convert DataYears to "unambiguous date format" for each imported objects (previously was a factor)
Gregorovitch$DateYears <- as.Date(Gregorovitch$DateYears, format = "%d/%m/%Y")
Ollivander$DateYears <- as.Date(Ollivander$DateYears, format = "%d/%m/%Y")

# convert to XTS/Zoo time series objects
Gregorovitch <- xts(Gregorovitch, order.by=Gregorovitch$DateYears)
Ollivander <- xts(Ollivander, order.by=Ollivander$DateYears)
  1. Bind the two xts objects together and create a dygraph from it. Utilize the help() index if youre stuck. Reminder
  • Give an effective title and x/y axes.
  • Label each Series (via dySeries) to be the appropriate wand-maker. So, one line should create a label for Ollivander and the other for Gregorovitch.
  • Stack this graph and modify the two lines to be different colors (and not the default ones!) Any colors are fine, but make sure theyre visible and that Ollivander is a different color than Gregorovitch.
  • Activate a range selector and make it big enough to view.
  • Use dyShading to illuminate approximately when Voldemort was revived and at-large: between 1995 to 1999.
  • Enable Highlighting on the graph, so mousing over a line bolds it.
# bind the 2 XTS object together
wandsPurchased <- cbind(Gregorovitch, Ollivander)

dygraph(wandsPurchased, main="Wands Purchased in Gregorovitch & Ollivander 1970-2017", xlab="Years", ylab="Wands Purchased") %>%
  dyRangeSelector() %>%
  dyShading(from = "1995-1-1", to = "1999-1-1") %>%
  dySeries("Wands", label="Gregorovitch", color="blue") %>%
  dySeries("Wands.1", label="Ollivander", color="red") %>%
  dyHighlight(highlightCircleSize = 3, 
              highlightSeriesBackgroundAlpha = 0.5,
              hideOnMouseOut = TRUE) %>%
  dyLegend(show = "follow")
